08031nam a22011175i 9789048552108DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485521087 a10.1515/97890485521082doi  a(DE-B1597)567843  a(OCoLC)1204634833  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aSOC0070002bisacsh00aReligion, Hypermobility and Digital Media in Global Asia :bFaith, Flows and Fellowship /ced. by Orlando Woods, Catherine Gomes, Lily Kong. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (258 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMedia, Culture and Communication in Migrant Societies ;v100tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- tSection 1. Community Creation: The Role of Digital Media in Faith-Based Groups -- t1. The Creation of Digitally-Mediated Christian Migrant Communities in Singapore -- t2. The Blog as a Platform for Spiritual Heritaging and Family Reconciliation : A Case Study -- t3. Material Expressions of Religious Culture -- tSection 2. Connectivity Through Faith: Maintaining Transnational Connections Through Religion -- t4. This-worldly Buddhism: Digital Media and the Performance of Religiosity in China -- t5. Forging Chinese Christian Digital Fellowship : Social Media and Transnational Connectivity -- tSection 3. Preaching the Faith: The Rise of Digital Pastors and Preachers -- t6. The Global Appeal of Digital Pastors : A Comparative Case Study of Joseph Prince, and Brian and Bobbie Houston -- t7. The ‘Open Letter to the Evangelical Church’ and its Discontents : The Online Politics of Asian American Evangelicals, 2013-2016 -- t8. Preacher Playlist: Reception and Curation of Celebrity Pastors in the Korean Diaspora -- t9. Virtual Rohingya: Ethno-Religious Populism in the Asia Pacific -- tAfterword -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDigital media is changing the ways in which religion is practiced, understood, proselytised and countered. Religious institutions and leaders use digital media to engage with their congregations who now are not confined to single locations and physical structures. The faithful are part of online communities which allow them a space to worship and to find fellowship. Migrant and mobile subjects thus are able to be connected to their faith - whether home grown or emerging - wherever they may be; thus providing them with an anchor in unfamiliar physical and cultural surroundings. As Asia rises, mobilities associated with Asian populations have escalated. The notion of 'Global Asia' is a reflection of this increased mobility, where Asia includes not only Asian countries as sites of political independence, but also the transnational networks of Asian trans/migrants, and the diasporic settlements of Asian peoples all over the world. This collection features cutting edge research by scholars across disciplines seeking to understand the role and significance of religion among transnational mobile subjects in this age of digital media, and in particular, as experienced in Global Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDigital mediaxReligious aspects. 0aMass media in religionzAsia. 0aMass media in religion. 4aAsia. 4aContemporary Society. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 4aMedia studies. 4aMigration, immigration and emigration. 4aReligion: general. 4aSociology and Social History. 4aSouth Asia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aReligion, Digital Media, Global Asia, Hyper Mobility.1 aBee, Sng Bee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoh, Robbie B. H.,